Date: Tue 2 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AFP via Gulftimes, Qatar, 2 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.gulftimes.com/site/topics/article.asp?cu_no=2&item_no=46932&version=1&template_id=39&parent_id=21>

Mass poultry slaughter in Siberian villages
-----------------------------------------------
Health authorities in neighboring provinces of Russia and Kazakhstan
set about slaughtering poultry yesterday [1 Aug 2005] amid signs that
the deadly bird flu virus was steadily spreading westwards from
China, officials said. The chief sanitary doctor of the Siberian
province of Novosibirsk said that slaughtering of poultry would begin
today in 13 villages where avian flu had been detected, the H5N1
sub-type that can be transmitted to humans.
"The destruction will begin on 2 Aug 2005. Measures are being worked
out to compensate the birds' owners," Valery Mikheyev was quoted by
Itar-Tass news agency as saying. He played down the danger to people
living in the villages where the virus had been found.
"The state of health of the inhabitants of these areas gives no cause
for alarm," Mikheyev said. "Up to 6000 people are being checked per
day," he said.
In the neighboring Kazakh province of Pavlodar, meanwhile, officials
said they had slaughtered 2350 geese and 250 ducks, after some 600
poultry at a farm died from bird flu starting on 20 Jul 2005, the
Kazakh Sanitary and Epidemiological Agency said [see commentary].
Tests were under way to determine whether the cases in Kazakhstan
were of the H5N1 type.
So far, cases of H5N1 around the world have mainly been transmitted
between animals. But it has killed more than 60 people in Southeast
Asia since 2003, including in Viet Nam, Thailand, Cambodia and
Indonesia. The arrival of the virus in Russia was greeted with alarm
in some communities, amid expectations that bird flu could spread to
more densely populated western Russia.
The Kommersant newspaper reported that one poultry company in the
western Siberian province of Orenburg was preparing to shoot down
migratory birds flying over its territory. "The most dangerous thing
is that from Kazakhstan the route of migratory birds goes through the
European part of Russia where the poultry industry is concentrated,"
Kommersant quoted the company's director, Nikolai Khaustov, as
saying. "We have already distributed cartridges to volunteers who
will fire at all birds flying towards our factory. The situation is
alarming," Khaustov said.
