Date: Tue 2 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ABC - Australia, 2 Aug 2005 [abridged, edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2005/s1428173.htm>

Illegal bird trade may be contributing to spread of bird flu
-----------------------------------------------
The rapid spread of the deadly Asian bird flu virus is sparking
concerns about the effectiveness of the international containment
protocol.
The highly contagious strain of avian flu has now turned up in
poultry stocks in Siberia and Kazakhstan, and some health authorities
say it's only a matter of time before the disease hits European Union
countries.
Russian doctors have been quick to blame migratory birds flying in
from infected regions of China. But bird experts say an illegal trade
in poultry cannot be ruled out as the source of the latest outbreak.
In a bid to halt the spread of bird flu, all domestic birds in a
western Siberian region will be slaughtered today [2 Aug 2005].
That's thousands of geese, chickens and ducks from more than a dozen
villages.
Just over the border in Kazakhstan, the cull has been underway for
days, and a bird transport ban has been imposed on the affected areas.
The virus was 1st detected 2 weeks ago in the area, and the World
Health Organization has still yet to confirm that it is the highly
contagious strain of the virus, H5N1.
[Byline: Karen Barlow & Eleanor Hall]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[In their notification on HPAI to the OIE, 24 Jul 2005, the Russian
authorities indicated as follows: "The hemagglutinin subtype has been
preliminarily identified (from pathological material) as H5. After
confirmation by virus isolation, a separate notification will be
sent. Tests are being performed to determine the neuraminidase type."
Rather puzzling: so far there is still no official information about
the N (neuraminidase) serotyping of the H5 virus strain involved in
outbreaks in Russia, H5N1 remaining "suspected." And, in spite of
repeated newswires about a human case and about outbreaks in poultry,
there has been no official response at all from neighboring
Kazakhstan.
There are rumors about the northwestward spread of the disease in
Siberia from Novosibirsk to the oblasts (regions, administrative and
territorial divisions) Omsk and Tyumen (Tioumen); further information
and an official update are urgently needed.
A useful map, provided by OIE's Animal Health Information Department,
can be accessed at
<http://www.oie.int/cartes/RUS050729.jpg>.
- Mod.AS]
